s ground-breaking study is the first to consider Spanish Golden Age comedias as an archive of moral knowledge. Kallendorf has examined over 800 of these plays to illustrate how they provide insight into aspects of early modern experience such as food, sex, work, and money. Finally, Kallendorf engages the theoretical terminology of Marxist literary criticism to demonstrate the inherent ambiguity of cultural change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aDeadly sins in literature. 0aEthics in literature. 0aSpanish drama (Comedy)xHistory and criticism. 0aSpanish dramayClassical period, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Renaissance.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266101140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442661011423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442661011.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK